    <!-- 1. The problem: composing embellished functions -->
    <h3>The problem: composing embellished functions</h3>
    <p>You have functions that return a value <em>plus</em> a log string. You can't compose them with ordinary function composition because the types don't line up: <code>a → (b, string)</code> followed by <code>b → (c, string)</code> needs someone to unpack the pair and concatenate the logs. That "someone" is Kleisli composition.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:load initialCode={`; Functions that return a value AND a log message.
; Type: a -> (value . log-string)
; We can't use plain compose — the types don't match.

(define (to-upper s)
  (cons (string-upcase s) "to-upper "))

(define (to-words s)
  (cons (string-split s " ") "to-words "))

(display "to-upper: ")
(display (to-upper "hello world")) (newline)
(display "to-words: ")
(display (to-words "HELLO WORLD")) (newline)

; We want to compose them: string -> (list-of-strings . log)
; But (to-words (to-upper "hello")) won't work —
; to-words expects a string, not a pair.
`} />

    <details class="my-2">
      <summary class="text-xs text-gray-500 cursor-pointer">imperative equivalent</summary>
      <Repl client:load initialCode={`# Functions that return value + log
def to_upper(s):
    return (s.upper(), "to_upper ")

def to_words(s):
    return (s.split(), "to_words ")

print(f"to_upper: {to_upper('hello world')}")
print(f"to_words: {to_words('HELLO WORLD')}")

# to_words(to_upper("hello")) fails — type mismatch
`} />
    </details>

    <!-- 2. The Writer type and Kleisli composition -->
    <h3>The Writer type and Kleisli composition</h3>
    <p>The <strong>Writer</strong> type wraps a value with a log: <code>(value . log)</code>. Kleisli composition (<code>>=></code>, the "fish operator") extracts the value from the first function's result, feeds it to the second, and concatenates the logs. This is the composition rule for morphisms in the Kleisli category.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:load initialCode={`; Writer: (value . log-string)
; Kleisli composition (fish operator): (a -> Writer b) -> (b -> Writer c) -> (a -> Writer c)

(define (fish f g)
  (lambda (x)
    (let* ((p1 (f x))
           (p2 (g (car p1))))
      (cons (car p2)
            (string-append (cdr p1) (cdr p2))))))

; Our embellished functions
(define (to-upper s)
  (cons (string-upcase s) "to-upper "))

(define (to-words s)
  (cons (string-split s " ") "to-words "))

; Compose them with fish
(define to-upper-words (fish to-upper to-words))

(display "composed: ")
(display (to-upper-words "hello world")) (newline)
; => (("HELLO" "WORLD") . "to-upper to-words ")
; Value flows through. Logs accumulate.
`} />


    <details class="my-2">
      <summary class="text-xs text-gray-500 cursor-pointer">imperative equivalent</summary>
      <Repl client:load initialCode={`# Kleisli composition for Writer
def fish(f, g):
    def composed(x):
        val1, log1 = f(x)
        val2, log2 = g(val1)
        return (val2, log1 + log2)
    return composed

def to_upper(s):
    return (s.upper(), "to_upper ")

def to_words(s):
    return (s.split(), "to_words ")

to_upper_words = fish(to_upper, to_words)
print(to_upper_words("hello world"))
# (["HELLO", "WORLD"], "to_upper to_words ")
`} />
    </details>

    <!-- 3. Identity and the category laws -->
    <h3>Identity and the category laws</h3>
    <p>Every category needs an identity morphism. In the Kleisli category for Writer, identity returns the value unchanged and contributes an empty log. With identity and fish, we can verify the three category laws: left identity, right identity, and associativity.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:load initialCode={`; Kleisli identity: return value unchanged, empty log
(define (writer-id x)
  (cons x ""))

; Fish operator (from above)
(define (fish f g)
  (lambda (x)
    (let* ((p1 (f x))
           (p2 (g (car p1))))
      (cons (car p2)
            (string-append (cdr p1) (cdr p2))))))

(define (to-upper s)
  (cons (string-upcase s) "to-upper "))

; Left identity:  fish(id, f) = f
(define left  ((fish writer-id to-upper) "hello"))
(define direct (to-upper "hello"))
(display "left identity:  ") (display (equal? left direct)) (newline)

; Right identity: fish(f, id) = f
(define right ((fish to-upper writer-id) "hello"))
(display "right identity: ") (display (equal? right direct)) (newline)

; Associativity: fish(fish(f, g), h) = fish(f, fish(g, h))
(define (to-words s) (cons (string-split s " ") "to-words "))
(define (count-em xs) (cons (length xs) "count "))

(define lhs ((fish (fish to-upper to-words) count-em) "hello world"))
(define rhs ((fish to-upper (fish to-words count-em)) "hello world"))
(display "associativity:  ") (display (equal? lhs rhs)) (newline)
(display "result: ") (display lhs)
; (2 . "to-upper to-words count ")
`} />


    <!-- 4. Logging as a real use case -->
    <h3>Logging as a real use case</h3>
    <p>The Writer monad lets you add logging to pure functions without mutation. Each function declares what it logs in its return type. Composition handles the plumbing. No global mutable log. No side effects. Just functions and types.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:load initialCode={`; A pipeline of "audited" functions — each logs what it did.

(define (fish f g)
  (lambda (x)
    (let* ((p1 (f x))
           (p2 (g (car p1))))
      (cons (car p2)
            (string-append (cdr p1) (cdr p2))))))

(define (validate-age n)
  (if (and (>= n 0) (<= n 150))
      (cons n "validated ")
      (cons -1 "INVALID ")))

(define (categorize n)
  (cond ((< n 0)  (cons "invalid" "categorized "))
        ((< n 18) (cons "minor" "categorized "))
        ((< n 65) (cons "adult" "categorized "))
        (else     (cons "senior" "categorized "))))

(define (format-result cat)
  (cons (string-append "Category: " cat) "formatted "))

(define pipeline (fish (fish validate-age categorize) format-result))

(display (pipeline 25)) (newline)
; ("Category: adult" . "validated categorized formatted ")
(display (pipeline 200)) (newline)
; ("Category: invalid" . "INVALID categorized formatted ")
; Every step is pure. The log assembles itself through composition.
`} />

    <details class="my-2">
      <summary class="text-xs text-gray-500 cursor-pointer">imperative equivalent</summary>
      <Repl client:load initialCode={`# Logging pipeline — no mutation, no global state
def fish(f, g):
    def composed(x):
        val1, log1 = f(x)
        val2, log2 = g(val1)
        return (val2, log1 + log2)
    return composed

def validate_age(n):
    if 0 <= n <= 150:
        return (n, "validated ")
    return (-1, "INVALID ")

def categorize(n):
    if n < 0: return ("invalid", "categorized ")
    if n < 18: return ("minor", "categorized ")
    if n < 65: return ("adult", "categorized ")
    return ("senior", "categorized ")

def format_result(cat):
    return (f"Category: {cat}", "formatted ")

pipeline = fish(fish(validate_age, categorize), format_result)
print(pipeline(25))
print(pipeline(200))
`} />
    </details>

    <!-- 5. Beyond Writer: the Kleisli pattern -->
    <h3>Beyond Writer: the Kleisli pattern</h3>
    <p>Writer is just one Kleisli category. Replace <code>(value . log)</code> with <code>(value | nothing)</code> and you get the <strong>Maybe/Optional</strong> monad for partial functions. Replace it with a list and you get <strong>nondeterminism</strong>. The pattern is always the same: define a type embellishment, a composition rule, and an identity. If the laws hold, you have a Kleisli category.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:load initialCode={`; Kleisli category for partial functions (Optional/Maybe)
; Embellishment: value OR 'nothing

(define (fish-maybe f g)
  (lambda (x)
    (let ((result (f x)))
      (if (eq? result 'nothing)
          'nothing
          (g result)))))

(define (maybe-id x) x)

; Safe reciprocal: fails on zero
(define (safe-recip x)
  (if (= x 0) 'nothing (/ 1 x)))

; Safe square root: fails on negative
(define (safe-root x)
  (if (< x 0) 'nothing (sqrt x)))

; Compose: safe-root-of-reciprocal
(define safe-root-recip (fish-maybe safe-recip safe-root))

(display "1/4 then sqrt: ") (display (safe-root-recip 4)) (newline)
; 0.5
(display "1/0 then sqrt: ") (display (safe-root-recip 0)) (newline)
; nothing — failure propagates
(display "1/(-1) then sqrt: ") (display (safe-root-recip -1)) (newline)
; nothing — reciprocal is -1, sqrt fails
`} />


